<br>
The reason I suggested my heal with a star ruby component, is that based on my preliminary model, the only heal that makes a real difference is something like a complete heal.  If it had no limitations, it would obsolete mend companion, which should be more useful anyway.  Choosing among our existing components, I reasoned that malachite is either too cheap, or would obselete Elemental Pact, pearl was too cheap, but star ruby is already used and is sufficiently expensive to limit its use.  I figure anyone who is putting Yakesha's on their pet surely won't balk at spending 60 pp to save their pet.<br>
<br>
Looks like my simple model is too simple, as it ignores hitpoints, and that medium quality heals, like the one suggested by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Wezloc</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are useful.<br>
<br>
To my mind then, the question then becomes to make sure that a new heal serves a useful purpose without being better than chaining, which is a powerful techinique. As an earlier poster correctly points out, a heal that was too good would have all the advantages of chaining with none of the disadvantages, and in fact would be much better than chaining.  The new heal should also be less effective than nuking in closing the second gap, as mages are and should be better at nuking than healing.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Wezloc</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s proposal, while better than any existing heal, seems initially both moderate and significant.<br>
<br>
I also think that any heal short of a CH should require no component other than mana.<br>
<br>
